ion.\n\nWebsite: clickslice.co.uk\nYouTube: Joshua George (40K+)\nBest for: Client SEO and agency methodology\n\nGlen Allsopp ,  @ViperChill \u00b7 30K+ followers\nGlen Allsopp has earned his recognition as one of the most respected investigative journalists in SEO. The founder of Detailed.com whose deep-dive analysis of what top-ranking sites actually do has exposed patterns that surface-level tools and surface-level practitioners consistently miss. His newsletter reaches 15,000+ subscribers who rely on it for competitive intelligence.\n\nWebsite: detailed.com\nNewsletter: Detailed (15K+)\nBest for: Investigative SEO analysis and competitive intelligence\n\nKyle Roof ,  @kaborz \u00b7 15K+ followers\nKyle Roof has earned recognition as the practitioner who has done more to advance on-page SEO testing methodology than almost anyone else. A co-founder of PageOptimizer Pro whose correlation studies and controlled experiments have changed how the entire industry thinks about content scoring and on-page optimization.\n\nWebsite: pageoptimizer.pro\nYouTube: Kyle Roof (20K+)\nBest for: On-page SEO testing and correlation studies\n\n\n3,500+ blogs published. 92% average SEO score. See what Stacc can do for your site. Most businesses publish 2 articles per month. Stacc publishes 30.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nThese are the people who build Google Search, and they have earned recognition as the most authoritative sources of information about how it actually works. When they post, it is the closest thing to an official statement in the entire SEO industry. Follow all 4.\nJohn Mueller ,  @JohnMu \u00b7 150K+ followers\nJohn Mueller holds a unique position of authority on this list as Google's Search Advocate. The practitioner who participates in SEO discussions in real time, clarifies misconceptions, and delivers official guidance directly to the community. His posts are sometimes cryptic but always worth reading, and no X feed is complete without him.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nBest for: Official Google guidance and SEO myth-busting\n\nDanny Sullivan ,  @dannysullivan \u00b7 300K+ followers\nDanny Sullivan has earned recognition as the single most authoritative public voice on Google's search policies and algorithm direction. The Search Liaison who communicates official Google positions on quality, updates, and policy changes. Before joining Google, he founded Search Engine Land, and his posts are the closest thing to an official Google SEO statement that exists.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nBest for: Official Google communications and policy updates\n\nGary Illyes ,  @methode \u00b7 80K+ followers\nGary Illyes has earned his recognition as the most technically direct voice from inside Google on crawling, indexing, and Googlebot behavior. A Search Analyst whose insights help developers and SEOs understand the infrastructure of search with a depth that official documentation rarely provides.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nBest for: Crawling, indexing, and Googlebot behavior\n\nMartin Splitt ,  @g33konaut \u00b7 40K+ followers\nMartin Splitt has earned recognition as the essential Google voice for anyone working with JavaScript, SPAs, or modern web frameworks. A Developer Relations Engineer who explains how Google renders pages and processes dynamic content in ways that make the difference between being indexed and being invisible.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search\nYouTube: Google Search Central\nBest for: JavaScript SEO and rendering from Google's perspective\n\n\nThese accounts have earned recognition as the most valuable brand voices on X for SEO practitioners. The tool companies and media outlets whose content goes beyond product promotion to deliver genuine education and data. Follow the ones whose tools you use.\nAhrefs ,  @aaborz \u00b7 200K+ followers\nAhrefs has earned recognition as the most educationally valuable brand account in SEO. An official presence that posts data studies, tool updates, and SEO tips sourced from one of the largest web indexes in the world. Their threads on ranking factors and search behavior patterns are among the most cited on the platform.\n\nWebsite: ahrefs.com\nYouTube: Ahrefs (620K+)\nBest for: Data-driven SEO research and tool updates\n\nSemrush ,  @semrush \u00b7 250K+ followers\nSemrush has earned recognition as the brand account that has done the most to make SEO education entertaining and accessible on X. Mixing memes, data threads, and tool announcements in a way that achieves consistently high engagement without sacrificing substance.\n\nWebsite: semrush.com\nYouTube: Semrush (250K+)\nBest for: Engaging SEO education and industry memes\n\nMoz ,  @Moz \u00b7 500K+ followers\nMoz has earned recognition as the SEO brand with the largest and most engaged following on X. A platform that has shaped the community for over a decade through Whiteboard Friday, algorithm analysis, and genuine curation of voices from across the SEO industry.\n\nWebsite: moz.com\nYouTube: Moz (95K+)\nBest for: Community-driven SEO education and Whiteboard Friday\n\nScreaming Frog ,  @scaborz \u00b7 30K+ followers\nScreaming Frog has earned recognition as one of the most practically useful technical SEO brand accounts on X. A team that posts tips on using their crawler for SEO audits and shares case studies from their agency work that demonstrate the depth of expertise behind the tool.\n\nWebsite: screamingfrog.co.uk\nBest for: Technical SEO and crawl analysis tips\n\nSE Ranking ,  @SERanking \u00b7 20K+ followers\nSE Ranking has earned its recognition for producing educational content on keyword tracking, competitor analysis, and site audits that is genuinely tool-agnostic and useful to practitioners regardless of which platform they use. A rarity among brand accounts.\n\nWebsite: seranking.com\nBest for: SEO platform updates and educational content\n\nSurfer SEO ,  @SurferSEO \u00b7 15K+ followers\nSurfer SEO has earned recognition for producing some of the most accessible and actionable content on NLP scoring and on-page optimization on X. Threads on content scoring and optimization signals that are useful to anyone doing content optimization, regardless of which tools they use.\n\nWebsite: surferseo.com\nBest for: Content optimization and NLP-based SEO\n\nSearch Engine Journal ,  @sejournal \u00b7 500K+ followers\nSearch Engine Journal has earned recognition as one of the fastest and highest-volume sources for SEO news and expert commentary on X. Posting 10+ articles per day and serving as one of the largest SEO media accounts on the entire platform.\n\nWebsite: searchenginejournal.com\nBest for: High-volume SEO news and expert interviews\n\nSearch Engine Land ,  @sengineland \u00b7 400K+ followers\nSearch Engine Land has earned its recognition for combining breaking SEO news with editorial analysis that provides context when algorithm updates and industry shifts happen. One of the most trusted sources for understanding not just what changed, but why it matters.\n\nWebsite: searchengineland.com\nBest for: Editorial SEO analysis and industry news\n\n\nSkip the agency. Keep the results. Stacc starts at $99/mo with a $1 launch trial. 30 articles per month. No deadlines to chase.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nThese accounts have earned recognition as the most influential educators and community builders in SEO. The voices who have invested in teaching the next generation of practitioners and building spaces where the industry comes together. Follow them if you are learning or want to connect with peers.\nAreej AbuAli ,  @AreejAbuAli \u00b7 25K+ followers\nAreej AbuAli has earned recognition as the founder of one of the most impactful communities in SEO. Women in Tech SEO, whose reach and influence extend far beyond its membership numbers. She posts about technical SEO, career growth, and community building with an authenticity that has made her one of the most respected voices on X.\n\nWebsite: womenintech.seo\nLinkedIn: 15K+ followers\nBest for: SEO community and career development\n\nCrystal Carter ,  @CrystalLCarterr \u00b7 15K+ followers\nCrystal Carter has earned her recognition as one of the clearest communicators of structured data and Google's rich result ecosystem on X. A Head of SEO Communications at Wix and co-host of the SERP's Up podcast whose threads translate complex Google documentation into actionable advice that practitioners can apply immediately.\n\nWebsite: wix.com/seo\nLinkedIn: 25K+ followers\nBest for: Structured data and SERP features\n\nCarolyn Lyden ,  @CarolynLyden \u00b7 10K+ followers\nCarolyn Lyden has earned her recognition as one of the most grounded and practically focused voices on search intent, content strategy, and local SEO on X. A Lead SEO who also advocates for diversity in the industry and brings a perspective that combines technical expertise with genuine community investment.\n\nWebsite: searchhermit.com\nBest for: Search intent analysis and SEO career advice\n\nDan Shure ,  @dan_shure \u00b7 12K+ followers\nDan Shure has earned recognition as the host of one of SEO's most intellectually rigorous interview formats. A practitioner whose Experts on the Wire podcast pushes guests past surface-level answers into the kind of deep thinking about keyword research, information architecture, and content strategy that is rare in the industry.\n\nWebsite: evolvingseo.com\nBest for: Deep SEO conversations and keyword research methodology\n\nLoren Baker ,  @lorenbaker \u00b7 15K+ followers\nLoren Baker has earned his recognition as one of the most historically significant voices in SEO media. The founder of Search Engine Journal in 2003 whose 20+ year perspective on the industry provides context and continuity that newer voices simply cannot offer.\n\nWebsite: searchenginejournal.com\nBest for: SEO industry perspective and community leadership\n\nTommy Griffith ,  @TommyGriffith \u00b7 10K+ followers\nTommy Griffith has earned recognition for bringing rare enterprise-level SEO experience to practitioner education. A founder of ClickMinded who previously led SEO at both Airbnb and PayPal and whose insider knowledge informs practical advice that benefits businesses of all sizes.\n\nWebsite: clickminded.com\nBest for: Startup SEO and enterprise SEO training\n\n\nThese accounts have earned recognition as the most essential voices to follow as AI search changes the entire discipline. The practitioners and engineers who are ahead of the generative engine optimization curve and whose insights will define how organic visibility works in the years ahead.\nFabrice Canel ,  @faaborz \u00b7 15K+ followers\nFabrice Canel has earned recognition as the authoritative voice from inside Microsoft Bing on how the world's second-largest search engine crawls, indexes, and ranks. A Principal Program Manager whose insights into BingBot behavior and Bing AI are essential for anyone optimizing beyond Google.\n\nWebsite: bing.com/webmasters\nBest for: Bing SEO and search engine engineering\n\nWil Reynolds (also in Agency section) regularly posts about AI disruption in search and how agencies need to adapt. His threads on preparing for AI Overviews combine data from Seer Interactive client campaigns with strategic foresight.\nKevin Indig (also in Strategy section) publishes the most data-backed analysis of AI search disruption on X. His Growth Memo newsletter covers how generative engine optimization is changing the SEO playbook.\nLily Ray (also in Algorithm section) covers AI Overviews extensively. Her analysis of which queries trigger AI Overviews and how they affect click-through rates is the most cited data on the topic.\n\nThese accounts have earned recognition as the rising voices delivering some of the highest-quality, most original SEO content on X. Practitioners with smaller followings whose signal-to-noise ratio rivals that of anyone with ten times their audience. Following them now puts you ahead of the curve.\n\nSteve Toth ,  @stevetoth \u00b7 10K+ followers\nSteve Toth has earned his recognition for delivering the most consistently focused, no-fluff tactical SEO advice on X. A practitioner whose SEO Notebook newsletter reaches 16,000+ subscribers and whose posts match that same standard: short, specific, and immediately usable.\n\nWebsite: seonotebook.com\nNewsletter: SEO Notebook (16K+)\nBest for: Single-tactic SEO advice\n\nNick Zviadadze ,  @nick_zviad \u00b7 8K+ followers\nNick Zviadadze has earned recognition as one of the most systematic voices on building repeatable SEO processes. A practitioner whose threads on ranking workflows are practical for agency owners and in-house teams who need to move beyond ad-hoc SEO and build something scalable. His YouTube channel adds detailed visual walkthroughs to his written content.\n\nWebsite: nickz.co\nYouTube: Nick Zviadadze (15K+)\nBest for: SEO workflows and process optimization\n\nKasra Dash ,  @KasraDash \u00b7 8K+ followers\nKasra Dash has earned recognition for bringing an information science perspective to topical authority and semantic SEO that sets his content apart from every other voice in this category. His threads on building topical maps are among the most detailed and intellectually rigorous on X.\n\nWebsite: kasra.co\nBest for: Topical authority and semantic SEO frameworks\n\nSuganthan Mohanadasan ,  @Suganthanmn \u00b7 12K+ followers\nSuganthan Mohanadasan has earned recognition as one of the most technically sophisticated enterprise SEO practitioners sharing insights on X. A consultant whose log file analysis, crawl optimization, and site performance content draws on enterprise-scale project data that most practitioners never encounter.\n\nBest for: Enterprise technical SEO and crawl data analysis\n\nSam Underwood ,  @SamUnderwoodUK \u00b7 6K+ followers\nSam Underwood has earned recognition as one of the most practically grounded voices on UK-focused SEO agency growth and local search. A practitioner who backs his threads with actual traffic data from real client wins that give his advice a credibility and specificity that most voices in this category lack.\n\nBest for: UK-focused SEO agency growth and local SEO\n\nLazarina Stoy ,  @lazarinastoy \u00b7 8K+ followers\nLazarina Stoy has earned her recognition for bridging data engineering and search marketing with a sophistication that is genuinely rare on X. A practitioner whose threads on using machine learning for SEO tasks make advanced data science techniques accessible to working SEOs.\n\nBest for: Data science for SEO and Python automation\n\nSara Taher ,  @Sara_Taher \u00b7 5K+ followers\nSara Taher has earned her recognition as an active voice at the intersection of technical SEO, content strategy, and career development in the SEO industry. A consultant and speaker whose work within the Women in Tech SEO community amplifies her impact well beyond her follower count.\n\nBest for: Technical SEO and career development\n\nRobbie Richards ,  @RobbieRichMktg \u00b7 15K+ followers\nRobbie Richards has earned recognition for producing some of the most thorough SEO guides and detailed tactical tutorials available anywhere on the internet. A practitioner whose posts on keyword research, link building, and content-driven growth deliver the same depth that made his website a benchmark in the industry.\n\nWebsite: robbierichards.com\nBest for: Detailed SEO tutorials and growth frameworks\n\n\nGlen Gabe ,  @GlenGabe \u00b7 20K+ followers\nGlen Gabe has earned recognition as one of the most diligent algorithm update analysts in SEO. A specialist in site recovery whose detailed breakdowns after every major Google update provide the empirical grounding that practitioners need to respond effectively.\n\nWebsite: gsqi.com\nBest for: Google algorithm recovery and penalty analysis\n\nMike Ramsey ,  @MikeRamsey \u00b7 15K+ followers\nMike Ramsey has earned recognition as a consistently practical voice on local SEO and citation strategies for small businesses. A practitioner whose insights on local pack rankings and map optimization are grounded in real results for real clients.\n\nWebsite: niftymarketing.com\nBest for: Local search strategy and small business SEO\n\nBlake Denman ,  @BlakeDenman \u00b7 8K+ followers\nBlake Denman has earned recognition as a reliable and tactical voice on Google Business Profile optimization. A local SEO specialist and frequent conference speaker whose advice on local ranking factors is directly actionable for practitioners managing GBP listings.\n\nWebsite: ricketyroo.com\nBest for: Local SEO tactics and Google Business Profile optimization\n\nMary Bowling ,  @MaryBowling \u00b7 12K+ followers\nMary Bowling has earned her recognition as a true pioneer of local SEO. A practitioner who has been shaping local search strategy since before Google Maps existed and whose foundational perspective remains essential for anyone working in multi-location SEO.\n\nWebsite: ignitvisibility.com\nBest for: Local search fundamentals and multi-location SEO\n\nMatthew Woodward ,  @MatthewWoodward \u00b7 25K+ followers\nMatthew Woodward has earned recognition for running one of the most data-backed SEO blogs in the industry. A practitioner whose link building experiments and traffic growth reports are grounded in real results that practitioners can study and apply to their own campaigns.\n\nWebsite: matthewwoodward.co.uk\nBest for: SEO case studies and link building experiments\n\nKate Toon ,  @KateToon \u00b7 15K+ followers\nKate Toon has earned her recognition for making technical SEO accessible to non-technical business owners in a way that few other voices manage. A coach and copywriter whose ability to translate complex SEO concepts into clear, actionable guidance has helped thousands of small businesses take ownership of their search visibility.\n\nWebsite: katetoon.com\nBest for: SEO for small businesses and SEO copywriting\n\nChima Mmeje ,  @ChimaMmeje \u00b7 10K+ followers\nChima Mmeje has earned her recognition as one of the clearest and most strategic voices on content clusters and topical authority frameworks on X. A practitioner whose breakdown of how to build content that dominates SERPs is both conceptually rigorous and immediately practical.\n\nWebsite: chimammeje.com\nBest for: Content clusters and topical authority frameworks\n\nAndrew Holland ,  @AndrewHollandSEO \u00b7 8K+ followers\nAndrew Holland has earned his recognition for bringing a refreshingly business-outcome-focused perspective to SEO strategy. A practitioner whose Growth Through Content newsletter and X posts consistently align SEO work with the revenue results that actually matter to stakeholders.\n\nWebsite: andrewholland.co\nBest for: SEO strategy for business growth\n\nNick LeRoy ,  @NickLeRoy \u00b7 10K+ followers\nNick LeRoy has earned recognition as one of the most candid and practically useful voices on freelance SEO strategy and client management on X. An independent consultant whose newsletter and posts give practitioners the honest insights on running an SEO consulting practice that more prominent voices rarely share.\n\nWebsite: nickleroy.com\nBest for: Freelance SEO strategy and consulting insights\n\nJason Barnard ,  @JasonBarnard \u00b7 12K+ followers\nJason Barnard has earned his recognition as the leading expert on brand SERPs and knowledge panels. The practitioner who has done more than anyone to advance the field of entity SEO and help businesses control how Google understands and represents them in search results.\n\nWebsite: jasonbarnard.com\nBest for: Entity SEO and brand SERP optimization\n\nViola Eva ,  @ViolaEva_ \u00b7 8K+ followers\nViola Eva has earned her recognition for championing sustainable, ethical SEO practices at a time when the industry is flooded with shortcuts. A practitioner whose content on long-term growth strategies provides a principled alternative to the tactics that win in the short term and destroy value in the long term.\n\nWebsite: flowseo.co\nBest for: Ethical SEO practices and sustainable growth strategies\n\nStacey MacNaught ,  @StaceyMacNaught \u00b7 10K+ followers\nStacey MacNaught has earned recognition as one of the most skilled digital PR strategists sharing campaign intelligence on X. A practitioner whose teardowns of real campaigns that generated high-authority links for major brands give practitioners an unusually direct window into what makes digital PR work at scale.\n\nWebsite: staceymacnaught.co.uk\nBest for: Digital PR strategy and outreach campaigns\n\nAmanda Jordan ,  @AmandaJordanSEO \u00b7 6K+ followers\nAmanda Jordan has earned her recognition as a local SEO specialist and community builder whose actionable local search tactics and advocacy for inclusive marketing bring a distinctive and valuable perspective to the field.\n\nWebsite: amandajordanseo.com\nBest for: Local SEO and community-focused marketing\n\nClaire Carlile ,  @ClaireCarlieSEO \u00b7 8K+ followers\nClaire Carlile has earned recognition as one of the most knowledgeable Google Business Profile consultants sharing expertise on X. A local SEO practitioner whose GBP tips and local visibility strategies are grounded in hands-on client work and genuine expertise.\n\nWebsite: clairecarlile.com\nBest for: Google Business Profile optimization and local visibility\n\nSam Dunning ,  @SamDunning_ \u00b7 10K+ followers\nSam Dunning has earned recognition as one of the most focused voices on B2B SEO and pipeline growth on X. A host of the Breaking B2B podcast whose content on lead generation and SEO for SaaS addresses the specific challenges that B2B marketers face with a depth of specialist knowledge that generalist SEO accounts rarely provide.\n\nWebsite: breakingb2b.com\nBest for: B2B SEO and lead generation\n\nMark Webster ,  @MarkWebster \u00b7 15K+ followers\nMark Webster has earned recognition as one of the most experienced authority site builders sharing strategy on X. A co-founder of Authority Hacker whose posts on affiliate SEO, content systems, and scaling niche sites draw on a track record of building and growing real sites with real traffic.\n\nWebsite: authorityhacker.com\nBest for: Authority site building and affiliate SEO\n\nPerrin Carrell ,  @PerrinCarrell \u00b7 5K+ followers\nPerrin Carrell has earned his recognition as a practitioner who shares the niche site strategy and content monetization insights that most experienced site builders keep to themselves. A voice whose posts on keyword targeting and site growth are grounded in the hands-on experience of building and growing real content businesses.\n\nWebsite: perrincarrell.com\nBest for: Niche site strategy and content monetization\n\nCarrie Hill ,  @Carrie_Hill_ \u00b7 8K+ followers\nCarrie Hill has earned her recognition as a true authority in local SEO. A LocalU co-founder whose years of hands-on experience managing local search strategy and multi-location accounts give her insights a depth and credibility that are rare in this category.\n\nWebsite: ignitvisibility.com\nBest for: Local search strategy and multi-location management\n\n\nDo not follow all 100 accounts and expect to absorb everything. That creates a noisy feed. Here is the approach that works.\nStep 1: Follow 15 to 20 accounts from this list. Pick 2 to 3 from each category that matches your role.\nStep 2: Create a private X List. Name it \"SEO Feed.\" Add your selected accounts. Check this list daily instead of your main timeline. Lists filter out the noise.\nStep 3: Turn on notifications for 3 to 5 key voices. Barry Schwartz for breaking news. Lily Ray for algorithm analysis. John Mueller for Google guidance. Pick the rest based on your specialty.\nStep 4: Engage within the first week. Reply to posts with specific thoughts. SEO X is a small community. Thoughtful replies get noticed by people with 100K+ followers. Engagement also trains the algorithm to show you more SEO content.\nStep 5: Audit your list monthly. Remove accounts that stopped posting or shifted topics. Add new voices you discover through conversations.\nStep 6: Cross-reference with other platforms. Many experts on this list also publish newsletters, YouTube channels, and LinkedIn content. Subscribe to 2 or 3 newsletters from your favorite voices.\n\n\n\n\nRank\nName\nHandle\nFollowers\nPrimary Focus\n\n\n\n\n1\nMoz\n@Moz\n500K+\nSEO education, community\n\n\n2\nSearch Engine Journal\n@sejournal\n500K+\nSEO news, expert interviews\n\n\n3\nAnn Handley\n@AnnHandley\n460K+\nContent writing, editorial\n\n\n4\nRand Fishkin\n@randfish\n450K+\nSearch strategy, audience research\n\n\n5\nNeil Patel\n@neilpatel\n450K+\nSEO education, marketing data\n\n\n6\nSearch Engine Land\n@sengineland\n400K+\nSEO news, editorial analysis\n\n\n7\nDanny Sullivan\n@dannysullivan\n300K+\nGoogle Search Liaison\n\n\n8\nSemrush\n@semrush\n250K+\nSEO tools, education\n\n\n9\nAhrefs\n@aaborz\n200K+\nData studies, tool updates\n\n\n10\nAleyda Solis\n@aleyda\n160K+\nInternational SEO, news\n\n\n11\nJoe Pulizzi\n@JoePulizzi\n150K+\nContent marketing\n\n\n12\nJohn Mueller\n@JohnMu\n150K+\nGoogle Search Advocate\n\n\n13\nBrian Dean\n@BrianEDean\n120K+\nLink building, content\n\n\n14\nLily Ray\n@liaborman\n109K+\nAlgorithm analysis, E-E-A-T\n\n\n15\nBarry Schwartz\n@rustybrick\n100K+\nBreaking SEO news\n\n\n16\nAndy Crestodina\n@caborz\n80K+\nContent marketing research\n\n\n17\nGary Illyes\n@methode\n80K+\nCrawling, indexing\n\n\n18\nAmanda Natividad\n@amandanat\n70K+\nZero-click content\n\n\n19\nKevin Indig\n@Kevin_Indig\n60K+\nGrowth strategy\n\n\n20\nRoss Simmonds\n@TheCoolestCool\n60K+\nContent distribution\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nYour Role\nFollow These Accounts\n\n\n\n\nSEO beginner\nNeil Patel, Moz, Ahrefs, Nathan Gotch, Crystal Carter\n\n\nIn-house SEO manager\nLily Ray, Barry Schwartz, Kevin Indig, Cyrus Shepard, John Mueller\n\n\nSEO agency owner\nMatt Diggity, Craig Campbell, Ryan Stewart, Wil Reynolds, Nathan Gotch\n\n\nContent marketer\nRoss Simmonds, Amanda Natividad, Ann Handley, Andy Crestodina, Julia McCoy\n\n\nTechnical SEO specialist\nMike King, JR Oakes, Cindy Krum, Martin Splitt, Bartosz Goralewicz\n\n\nLocal SEO practitioner\nJoy Hawkins, Darren Shaw, Greg Gifford, Mike Blumenthal, Ben Fisher\n\n\nLink builder\nPaddy Moogan, Dixon Jones, Bibi Raven, Page One Power, Siege Media\n\n\nSaaS marketer\nEli Schwartz, Brendan Hufford, Kevin Indig, Tim Soulo\n\n\nAI search optimizer\nLily Ray, Kevin Indig, Fabrice Canel, Danny Sullivan\n\n\n\n\nYour SEO team. $99 per month. Stacc publishes 30 optimized articles monthly. Every article stacks on the last. SEO compounds.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\n\nWho is the most-followed SEO expert on X?\nAmong pure SEO experts, Rand Fishkin and Neil Patel each have approximately 450K followers. Moz has the largest brand following at 500K+. Danny Sullivan has 300K+ as Google's Search Liaison. For daily practical advice, Neil Patel posts most frequently.\nHow many SEO accounts should I follow on X?\nFifteen to twenty is the sweet spot. Create a dedicated X List for your SEO follows. Following too many accounts dilutes your feed with noise. Pick 2 to 3 from each category that matches your work.\nIs X still relevant for SEO professionals in 2026?\nYes. X remains the fastest platform for SEO news. Algorithm updates, Google bugs, and ranking experiments surface on X hours before they appear on SEO blogs or newsletters. The real-time format is unmatched for breaking news.\nShould I follow SEO tool accounts or individual experts?\nFollow both. Tool accounts like Ahrefs and Semrush share data studies. Individual experts like Lily Ray and Barry Schwartz share analysis and opinions. The combination gives you raw data plus expert interpretation.\nHow do I find more SEO accounts to follow?\nCheck the replies on posts from the people listed here. X's algorithm surfaces active commenters. Also explore the speaker lists from BrightonSEO, MozCon, and SearchLove conferences. Conference speakers who are also active on X tend to be strong follows.\nWhat is the best time to check SEO X for updates?\nMonday through Friday between 9 AM and 12 PM ET sees the highest posting activity from SEO professionals. Google tends to confirm algorithm updates on weekdays during US business hours. Set up a daily 10-minute check of your SEO X List during this window.\nThe 100 SEO accounts listed above represent the most active and relevant search marketing voices on X in 2026. Build your list. Check it daily. Apply what you learn.\nFor the full picture of SEO voices across every platform, explore our lists of SEO influencers on Instagram, SEO influencers on LinkedIn, and SEO YouTube channels.\nDid we miss an essential SEO account on X? We update this list quarterly. Bookmark it and check back.\n\nStop researching. Start ranking. Stacc publishes 30 SEO articles per month on autopilot. Your content compounds while you focus on your business.\nStart for $1 \u2192\n\nAre you on this list? Email us with \"Best SEO X Accounts Badge\" in the subject and we will send you your badge embed code to display on your site.\n\nFree SEO Tools:\n- Free SEO Audit\n- On-Page SEO Checker\n- Website SEO Score\nBest Lists:\n- Best AI SEO Tools\n- Best SEO Automation Tools"
