<p><strong>Who is the most-followed SEO expert on X?</strong></p>
<p>Among pure SEO experts, Rand Fishkin and Neil Patel each have approximately 450K followers. Moz has the largest brand following at 500K+. Danny Sullivan has 300K+ as Google's Search Liaison. For daily practical advice, Neil Patel posts most frequently.</p>
<p><strong>How many SEO accounts should I follow on X?</strong></p>
<p>Fifteen to twenty is the sweet spot. Create a dedicated X List for your SEO follows. Following too many accounts dilutes your feed with noise. Pick 2 to 3 from each category that matches your work.</p>
<p><strong>Is X still relevant for SEO professionals in 2026?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. X remains the fastest platform for SEO news. Algorithm updates, Google bugs, and ranking experiments surface on X hours before they appear on <a href="/blog/best-seo-blogs/">SEO blogs</a> or newsletters. The real-time format is unmatched for breaking news.</p>
<p><strong>Should I follow SEO tool accounts or individual experts?</strong></p>
<p>Follow both. Tool accounts like Ahrefs and Semrush share data studies. Individual experts like Lily Ray and Barry Schwartz share analysis and opinions. The combination gives you raw data plus expert interpretation.</p>
<p><strong>How do I find more SEO accounts to follow?</strong></p>
<p>Check the replies on posts from the people listed here. X's algorithm surfaces active commenters. Also explore the speaker lists from BrightonSEO, MozCon, and SearchLove conferences. Conference speakers who are also active on X tend to be strong follows.</p>
<p><strong>What is the best time to check SEO X for updates?</strong></p>
<p>Monday through Friday between 9 AM and 12 PM ET sees the highest posting activity from SEO professionals. Google tends to confirm algorithm updates on weekdays during US business hours. Set up a daily 10-minute check of your SEO X List during this window.</p>
